The Battle of Neighborhoods Between New York City and the City of Toronto- Week Two¶

1.0 Introduction¶

New York City and the City of Toronto are very popular tourist and vacation destination for people all round the globe. Both cities are very diverse and are the financial capitals of their respective countries.

Firstly, New York City comprises five boroughs sitting where the Hudson River meets the Atlantic Ocean. At its core is Manhattan, a densely populated borough that's among the world's major commerncial, financial, and cultural centers, with an historial population data 18,804,000 in 2020.

In the same vain, Toronto with a polulation of 2,731,571 in 2016, it is the most populous city in Canada and the fouth most populous city in North America. Toronto, the capital of the provimce of Ontario, is also a shining an international centre of business, finance, arts, and culture, and recognized as one of the most multicultural and cosmopolitan cities in the world which attract businessmen and women to invest their money. Its economy is highly diversified with strengths in technology, design, financial services, life sciences, education, arts, fashion, aerospace, environmental innovation, food services and tourism.

It is important to say that, the seat of government of the Ontario legislature is at Queen's Park. Because of its provincial capital status, the city was also the location of Government House, the residence of the viceregal representative of the Crown in right of Ontario, so to locate the right place to establish business can be a challenge, though. so, what are the best way to get location information?

1.1 Business Understanding¶

In this analysis, I will compare the neighborhoods of the two cities and determine how similar or dissimilar they are. Is New York City more like Toronto?

The goals and objectives is to explore, segment, analyze and cluster The New York City and The City of Toronto.

Hence, three business requrements were identified.

1 Exploring the neighborhoods in New York City and the City of Toronto.

2 Analyzing each neighborhoods in New York City and the City of Toronto.

3 Clustering and determining the discriminating venues categories that distinguish each cluster.

As locating the best place to own business is challenging having to determine how similar or dissimilar they are, which could potentially available would be worthwhile. The target audience are investors.

2.0 Methodology¶

2.1 Analytic Approach¶

To analyze the neighborhood of New York City and the City of Toronto to compare their similarity or dissimilarity. I will use a K-means clustering: a type of unsupervised learning, which is used when have unlabelled data. Data points are clustered based on feature similarity. More interstingly, this algorithm is to find groups in the data with the number of groups represented by the variable k.

2.2 Data Requirement¶

Selecting a suitable location data from New York city and the City of Toronto

Thus, two criteria were identified:

Firstly, the postal codes of each borough and neighborhood to be used

latitude and longitude value of each borough and neighborhood to create a map

2.3 Data Understanding¶

In order to understand the data related to location; map, histogram, scatter plots were used to visualize the neighborhood of the two cities to understand their distribution using folium pacakage, matplotlib, numpy, and pandas methods in python.

2.4 Data Collection¶

Toronto¶

I scraped the Wikipedia page with BeautifulSoup library and wrangle the data, clean it, and then read it into a pandas dataframe.

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_postal_codes_of_Canada:_M

New York¶

I used pamdas method pd.json_normalize to load the data into dataframe and the JSON file was downloaded from the following website

https://cf-courses-data.s3.us.cloud-object-storage.appdomain.cloud/IBMDeveloperSkillsNetwork-DS0701EN-SkillsNetwork/labs/newyork_data.json

In order to get the latitude and longitude of all the boroughs and neighborhoods in the City of Toronto, the csv file was downloaded from https://cocl.us/Geospatial_data then I use pandas method read_csv to load the data into dataframe while geopy package was used to get the latitude and longitude of all the boroughs and neighborhoods in New York City.

I used Foursquare API to explore the neighborhoods in New York City and the City of Toronto. I used the explore function to get the most common venue categories in each neighborhood, and then use this feature to group the neighborhoods into clusters. I assigned the limit as 100 venues and the radius 500 meter for each borough from their given postal code, latitude and longititude. Foursquare is Technology company that provide location data with information about venues.

I used the k-means clustering algorithm to complete this task. K-means is a classic algorithm used for cluster analysis. The first step is to select k initial centroids. A centroid is simply the center of the cluster. Next, assigned each sample in a data set to the closest centroid. The sklearn library was used for the K-means analysis.

Finally, I employed the Folium library to visualize the neighborhoods in New York City and the City of Toronto and their emerging clusters.

2.5 Data Preparation¶

In order to clean the datasets, Firstly, I will use na_values method to convert Not assigned to NaN when downloading the Toronto datasets on the website. Then use pandas method dropna to remove it in the dataframe. After that I will create another dataframe for geospatial and Toronto in order to use pandas method merge to have column names Postal Codes, Borough, Neighborhood, Latitude, and Longitude in the same table for the City of Toronto datasets. I will also do some feature engineering for the New York City datasets.

# @hidden_cell
# function that extracts the category of the venue
def get_category_type(row):
    try:
        categories_list = row['categories']
    except:
        categories_list = row['venue.categories']
        
    if len(categories_list) == 0:
        return None
    else:
        return categories_list[0]['name']

# @hidden_cell
def getNearbyVenues(names, latitudes, longitudes, radius=500):
    
    venues_list=[]
    for name, lat, lng in zip(names, latitudes, longitudes):
        print(name)
            
        # create the API request URL
        url = 'https://api.foursquare.com/v2/venues/explore?&client_id={}&client_secret={}&v={}&ll={},{}&radius={}&limit={}'.format(
            CLIENT_ID, 
            CLIENT_SECRET, 
            VERSION, 
            lat, 
            lng, 
            radius, 
            LIMIT)
            
        # make the GET request
        results = requests.get(url).json()["response"]['groups'][0]['items']
        
        # return only relevant information for each nearby venue
        venues_list.append([(
            name, 
            lat, 
            lng, 
            v['venue']['name'], 
            v['venue']['location']['lat'], 
            v['venue']['location']['lng'],  
            v['venue']['categories'][0]['name']) for v in results])

    nearby_venues = pd.DataFrame([item for venue_list in venues_list for item in venue_list])
    nearby_venues.columns = ['Neighborhood', 
                  'Neighborhood Latitude', 
                  'Neighborhood Longitude', 
                  'Venue', 
                  'Venue Latitude', 
                  'Venue Longitude', 
                  'Venue Category']
    
    return(nearby_venues)

num_top_venues = 5

for hood in manhattan_grouped['Neighborhood']:
    print("----"+hood+"----")
    temp = manhattan_grouped[manhattan_grouped['Neighborhood'] == hood].T.reset_index()
    temp.columns = ['venue','freq']
    temp = temp.iloc[1:]
    temp['freq'] = temp['freq'].astype(float)
    temp = temp.round({'freq': 2})
    print(temp.sort_values('freq', ascending=False).reset_index(drop=True).head(num_top_venues))
    print('\n')

# @hidden_cell
def return_most_common_venues(row, num_top_venues):
    row_categories = row.iloc[1:]
    row_categories_sorted = row_categories.sort_values(ascending=False)
    
    return row_categories_sorted.index.values[0:num_top_venues]

# @hidden_cell
def get_geocode(postal_code):
    # initialize your variable to None
    lat_lng_coords = None
    while(lat_lng_coords is None):
        g = geocoder.google('{}, Toronto, Ontario'.format(postal_code))
        lat_lng_coords = g.latlng
    latitude = lat_lng_coords[0]
    longitude = lat_lng_coords[1]
    return latitude,longitude

# @hidden_cell
def getNearbyVenues(names, latitudes, longitudes, radius=500):
    
    venues_list=[]
    for name, lat, lng in zip(names, latitudes, longitudes):
        print(name)
            
        # create the API request URL
        url = 'https://api.foursquare.com/v2/venues/explore?&client_id={}&client_secret={}&v={}&ll={},{}&radius={}&limit={}'.format(
            CLIENT_ID, 
            CLIENT_SECRET, 
            VERSION, 
            lat, 
            lng, 
            radius, 
            LIMIT)
            
        # make the GET request
        results = requests.get(url).json()["response"]['groups'][0]['items']
        
        # return only relevant information for each nearby venue
        venues_list.append([(
            name, 
            lat, 
            lng, 
            v['venue']['name'], 
            v['venue']['location']['lat'], 
            v['venue']['location']['lng'],  
            v['venue']['categories'][0]['name']) for v in results])

    nearby_venues = pd.DataFrame([item for venue_list in venues_list for item in venue_list])
    nearby_venues.columns = ['Neighbourhood', 
                  'Neighbourhood Latitude', 
                  'Neighbourhood Longitude', 
                  'Venue', 
                  'Venue Latitude', 
                  'Venue Longitude', 
                  'Venue Category']
    
    return(nearby_venues)

# @hidden_cell
def return_most_common_venues(row, num_top_venues):
    row_categories = row.iloc[1:]
    row_categories_sorted = row_categories.sort_values(ascending=False)
    
    return row_categories_sorted.index.values[0:num_top_venues]

num_top_venues = 10

indicators = ['st', 'nd', 'rd']

# create columns according to number of top venues
columns = ['Neighbourhood']
for ind in np.arange(num_top_venues):
    try:
        columns.append('{}{} Most Common Venue'.format(ind+1, indicators[ind]))
    except:
        columns.append('{}th Most Common Venue'.format(ind+1))

# create a new dataframe
neighbourhoods_venues_sorted = pd.DataFrame(columns=columns)

4.0 Discussion¶

The analysis in table one revealed the most common venues in Manhattan borough and their neighbourhoods. Interestingly, out of the five clusters, Marble Hill have the most common venue at Sandwich Place, while Washington Heights have Cafe, at Inwood is Mexican Restaurant and at Hamilton Heights is Pizza Place. At Manhattan cluster two the most common venues are; Central Harlem is African Restaurant, at Upper East Side, Yorkvile, Lenox Hill, Greenwich Village, and Flatiron have Italian Restaurants while at Manhattan Valley is Mexican Restaurant, also at Midtown South have Korean Restaurant.

Again,in table two out of the five clusters at East Toronto in the city of Toronto, the merged table revealed that Greek Restaurant is the most common venue for Danforth West, Riverdale neighbourhood, while India Bazzar, The Beaches West have Fast Food Restaurant, Studio District have Coffe Shop, Business reply mail Processing Centre have Recording Studio.

In the onehot neighbouthoods in East Toronto, the merged talbe shows very reasonable mean values for the following venues such as Anarican Restaurant, Bakery, Bank, Bar, Bookshop, Brevery, Cafe, Cheese Shop, Chlothing Shop, Coffe Shop, Comfort Food Restaurant, Convenience Store, Coworking Space, Dinner, Fish Market, Gastropub, Gay Bar, Gym/Fitness Center, Ice Cream Shop, Italian Restaurant, Middle Eastern Restaurant, Park, Pet Shop, Seafood Restaurant,and Yoga Studio.

5.0 Conclusion¶

The present analysis aim at comparing the similarity or desimilarity between the city of New York and the city of Toronto. The similar od desimilar was revealed through the K-means clustering analysis. The results shown that New York City and The City of toronto are similar in international business context. It is demonstrated in the five clustered results.
